SIMPLE: sway
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sway
<hw>Sway</hw> <pr>(sw⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Swayed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Swaying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sweyen</ets>,
Icel. <ets>sveigja</ets>, akin to E. <ets>swing</ets>; cf. D.
<ets>zwaaijen</ets> to wield, swing. See <er>Swing</er>, and cf.
<er>Swag</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move or wield
with the hand; to swing; to wield; <as>as, to <ex>sway</ex> the
scepter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As sparkles from the anvil rise,⟦br⟧
When heavy hammers on the wedge are <qex>swayed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To influence or direct by power and authority; by
persuasion, or by moral force; to rule; to govern; to guide.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The will of man is by his reason <qex>swayed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She could not <qex>sway</qex> her house.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This was the race⟦br⟧
To <qex>sway</qex> the world, and land and sea subdue.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to incline or swing to one side, or
backward and forward; to bias; to turn; to bend; warp; <as>as, reeds
<ex>swayed</ex> by wind; judgment <ex>swayed</ex> by
passion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As bowls run true by being made⟦br⟧
On purpose false, and to be <qex>swayed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not temporal and little advantages <qex>sway</qex> you against
a more durable interest.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To hoist; <as>as, to
<ex>sway</ex> up the yards</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To bias; rule; govern; direct; influence; swing;
move; wave; wield.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1457 --></p>

<p><ent>Sway</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sway
<hw>Sway</hw> <pr>(sw⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
be drawn to one side by weight or influence; to lean; to
incline.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The balance <qex>sways</qex> on our part.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move or swing from side to side; or backward and
forward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To have weight or influence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The example of sundry churches . . . doth <qex>sway</qex>
much.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bear sway; to rule; to govern.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hadst thou <qex>swayed</qex> as kings should do.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sway</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sway
<hw>Sway</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of swaying; a
swaying motion; the swing or sweep of a weapon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With huge two-handed <qex>sway</qex> brandished aloft.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Influence, weight, or authority that inclines to one
side; <as>as, the <ex>sway</ex> of desires</as>.</def> <rj><au>A.
Tucker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Preponderance; turn or cast of balance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Expert⟦br⟧
When to advance, or stand, or turn the <qex>sway</qex>⟦br⟧
Of battle.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Rule; dominion; control.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When vice prevails, and impious men bear <qex>sway</qex>,⟦br⟧
The post of honor is a private station.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A switch or rod used by thatchers to bind their
work.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Rule; dominion; power; empire; control;
influence; direction; preponderance; ascendency.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sway-backed</ent>⟦br⟧
